==English==
{{webster}}
===Etymology===

From [[w:Latin|Latin]][[Category:Latin derivations]] [[extortus]], past participle of [[extorquere]] ''to [[twist]] or [[wrench]] out, to [[extort]]''; from [[ex]] ''out'' + [[torquere]] ''to turn about, twist''. See [[torsion]].

===Transitive verb===
'''to extort''' ('''extorting''', '''extorted''')
#To [[wrest]] from an [[unwilling]] person by physical force, menace, duress, torture, or any undue or illegal exercise of power or ingenuity; to wrench away (from); to [[tear]] away; to [[wring]] (from); to [[exact]]; as, to extort contributions from the vanquished; to extort confessions of guilt; to extort a promise; to extort payment of a debt. 
#(Law) To get by the offense of [[extortion]].
 
